markably successful in carefully reintegrating its members into Japanese society. It has become known as a model alternative to long-term institutionalization.‹/p›‹p›In ‹b›‹i›A Disability of the Soul‹/i›‹/b›, Karen Nakamura explores how the members of this unique community struggle with their lives, their illnesses, and the meaning of community. Told through engaging historical narrative, insightful ethnographic vignettes, and compelling life stories, her account of Bethel House depicts its achievements and setbacks, its promises and limitations. ‹b›‹i›A Disability of the Soul‹/i› ‹/b›is a sensitive and multidimensional portrait of what it means to live with mental illness in contemporary Japan.‹/p›  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity mental health servicesxJapanxUrakawa-chō. 0aCommunity mental health serviceszJapanzUrakawa-chō. 0aCommunity mental health serviceszJapanzUrakawa-chō. 0aMental illnessxSocial aspectsxJapan. 0aMental illnessxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aMentally illxRehabilitationxJapanxUrakawa-chō. 0aMentally illxRehabilitationzJapanzUrakawa-chō. 0aMentally illxRehabilitationzJapanzUrakawa-chō. 0aSchizophreniaxSocial aspectsxJapan. 0aSchizophreniaxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aSchizophrenicsxRehabilitationxJapanxUrakawa-chō. 0aSchizophrenicsxRehabilitationzJapanzUrakawa-chō. 0aSchizophrenicsxRehabilitationzJapanzUrakawa-chō. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies.  aCommunity mental health services in japan.  abethel house in japan.  abethel house.  abooks for masters in social work .  abooks for practicing mental health professionals.  abooks for practicing psychiatrists.  abooks for students in social work .  acommunity approach to psychosocial recovery.  acultural japanese history .  adisability in japan.  aeast asian studies.  ae